This paper focuses on user engagement patterns within a mobile health application, specifically related to physical activity tracking. The study involves analyzing large amounts of user data over a long period of time, which suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the use of notifications, recommendations, and gamification to increase engagement, which could fall under the categories of computational engineering, finance, and science (cs.CE) and information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper's focus on health and wellness could potentially fall under the category of computers and society (cs.CY).
